But if they saw what I had inside? Sure, I'd peeked at her glossy-covered artbooks with their full-page pictures in soft focus or grainy black and white. Sure, I'd smiled when I saw the lacy scraps of her monogrammed lingerie hanging to dry in the upstairs bathroom, soaked in the hints of the warm fur hidden by her everyday clothing. Sure, I'd muttered something about kids and toys when she left a human-shaped dildo out.
It just feels so excessive, for lack of a better word. There's too much detail to absorb in each paragraph, and that's a turn off to me because it forces me to go back and read it over multiple times. It feels like a chore to read, which is why I don't read Happy_Dragon.
